late twentieth century. In the Czech lands, Kieval writes, Jews have felt the need constantly to define and articulate the nature of group identity, cultural loyalty, memory, and social cohesiveness, and the period of "modernizing" absolutism, which began in 1780, brought changes of enormous significance. From that time forward, new relationships with Gentile society and with the culture of the state blurred the traditional outlines of community and individual identity. Kieval navigates skillfully among histories and myths as well as demography, biography, culture, and politics, illuminating the maze of allegiances and alliances that have molded the Jewish experience during these 200 years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aJewsxIdentity. 0aJewszCzech RepublicxIntellectual lifey18th century. 0aJewszCzech RepublicxIntellectual lifey19th century. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  aacculturation.  aantisemitism.  aashkenazim.  aassimilation.  abelonging.  abohemia.  abohemian jewish.  abohemian jewry.  abohmen.  abohmischen.  acentral europe.  acommunity.  aculture.  aczech republic.  aczech.  afolk tale.  afolklore.  agentiles.  agroup identity.  ahistory.  ajan hus.  ajewish experience.  ajewish life.  ajewish.  ajews.  ajudaica.  ajudaism.  akahal.  alanguage.  alinguistics.  amasaryk.  amemory.  amigration.  amoravia.  amyth.  anationalism.  anonfiction.  aplace.  aprague.  areligion.  areligious pluralism.  aritual murder.  aritual.  atradition.  ayiddish.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052021410140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092116040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520921160423Coveruhttps://ww